{"copyright": {"licenseType": "NO", "determinationType": "OTHER", "thirdPartyContentCondition": "NOT_SET"}, "subjectCategories": ["SOLAR PHYSICS"], "exportControl": {"isExportControl": "NO", "ear": "NO", "itar": "NO"}, "created": "2013-08-11T16:35:00.0000000+00:00", "distributionDate": "2011-08-17T00:00:00.0000000+00:00", "center": {"code": "CDMS", "name": "Legacy CDMS", "id": "092d6e0881874968859b972d39a888dc"}, "onlyAbstract": false, "sensitiveInformation": 2, "abstract": "The onsets of closely consecutive homologous flares (CCHF), which are separated by less than 6 hours and most often by about 1 hour, are compared with that of isolated flares (no flare in the region half a day before). Isolated flares appear to be formed of two components, a surging arch and a flaring arch, while a set of CCHF may be composed of consecutive elementary flares or of a series of complex ones. It is shown that the onset of eruptive flare phenomena is not the same for an isolated event and for a member of CCHF (excluding the first) as found in H-alpha and EUV observations, and probably in X-ray observations also. It is suggested that a CCHF set would become a single flare with episodic enhancement of brightness by taking account of the common H-alpha behavior of surging and flaring arches as well as the EUV emission.", "title": "About the onsets of closely-consecutive homologous flares", "stiType": "REPRINT", "distribution": "PUBLIC", "submittedDate": "2013-08-11T16:35:00.0000000+00:00", "isLessonsLearned": false, "authorAffiliations": [{"sequence": 0, "submissionId": 19830053995, "meta": {"author": {"name": "Martres, M. J."}, "organization": {"name": "Observatoire de Paris-Meudon", "location": "France"}}, "id": "333faae590254d8eb2d468acaa1affa4"}, {"sequence": 1, "submissionId": 19830053995, "meta": {"author": {"name": "Mein, N."}, "organization": {"name": "Observatoire de Paris-Meudon", "location": "France"}}, "id": "5bc659dafba94667a3f69641eb59d25c"}, {"sequence": 2, "submissionId